      <h4 class="blue"><strong>Tip 3:</strong> Track multiple page elements.</h4>
      <p>Keep in mind the reason you’re testing: you want to achieve a certain goal or goals. Many factors may affect the success of achieving your goal whether it be increasing views, sign-ups, leads, revenue, downloads or a combination of these. Tracking multiple elements on the pages you’re testing helps measure how your tests impact the different ways a visitor could achieve the goal. You will not only be able learn which experience was better by tracking multiple elements, but also possibly learn why it was better for your site visitors.</p>

      <p>For example, a software site has a goal to create more sales leads for their sales team. A visitor can become a lead in three ways:
        </p><ol>
          <li>Watching a video on the homepage that prompts them to “learn more” by filling out a form</li>
          <li>Clicking on the “take the guided tour” button which ends in a form to create an account</li>
          <li>Directly signing up for a 30-day free trial from the pricing page</li>
        </ol>
      <p></p>

      <p>The company runs AB tests to hopefully increase the number visitors who convert into leads. They track clicks on all three lead-generation sources to measure if and how any variation impacts that source. Maybe advertising the 30-day free trial detracts from visitors who become a lead via watching the video. Tracking clicks on both buttons will give the full picture on how to best optimize the page to achieve the ultimate goal of increasing leads.</p>
